Task 1 - Differences-in-Differences: A perfect storm (20 points)

As you all probably remember, a few weeks ago Texas was affected by one of the worst winter storms, causing great damage, including prolonged blackouts and water cuts. As an entrepreneur (and somewhat a causal inference nerd), you want to look on the bright side (?) and try to use this event for a differences-in-differences study on the impact of blackouts on the prices of flashlights. You know that Texas is on its own electricity grid, so even though more states were affected by the storm, Texas was the only one with extended power shuts.

You decide to collect data from Oklahoma, because as it is a neighboring state, would work well as a comparison group.

1) From a differences-in-differences standpoint, what would your two dimensions be in this case? (5 points)

2) What estimand would you be estimating in this case? Identify the treatment and control group (5 points)

3) What are potential problems that you might be concerned about in this setting, in terms of causal inference? What robustness checks would you run to make sure your main assumptions are more likely to hold? (10 points)

Task 2 - Randomized Controlled Trials and Matching: Going Green! (40 points)

The metropolitan Austin area is interested in helping residents become more environmentally conscious, reduce their water consumption, and save money on their monthly water bills. To do this, Hays, Comal, Guadalupe, and Travis counties have jointly initiated a new program that provides free rain barrels to families who request them. These barrels collect rain water, and the reclaimed water can be used for non-potable purposes (like watering lawns and gardens). Officials hope that families that use the barrels will rely more on rain water and will subsequently use fewer county water resources, thus saving both the families and the counties money.

Being evaluation-minded, the counties hired a consultant (you!) before rolling out their program. You convinced them to fund and run a randomized controlled trial (RCT) during 2019, and the counties rolled out the program city-wide in 2020. You have two datasets: barrels_rct.csv with data from the RCT, and barrels_obs.csv with observational data from self-selected participants.

These datasets contain the following variables:

  • id: A unique ID number for each household
  • water_bill: The familys average monthly water bill, in dollars
  • barrel: An indicator variable showing if the family participated in the program
  • barrel_num: A 0/1 numeric version of barrel
  • yard_size: The size of the familys yard, in square feet
  • home_garden: An indicator variable showing if the family has a home garden
  • home_garden_num: A 0/1 numeric version of home_garden
  • attitude_env: The familys self-reported attitude toward the environment, on a scale of 1-10 (10 meaning highest regard for the environment)
  • temperature: The average outside temperature (these get wildly unrealistic for the Atlanta area; just go with it)
library(tidyverse)

barrels_rct <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/website_github/master/exampleSite/content/files/data/barrels_rct.csv") %>% 
  # This makes it so "No barrel" is the reference category
  mutate(barrel = fct_relevel(barrel, "No barrel"))

barrels_obs <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/website_github/master/exampleSite/content/files/data/barrels_observational.csv") %>% 
  # This makes it so "No barrel" is the reference category
  mutate(barrel = fct_relevel(barrel, "No barrel"))

Task 3 - Regression Discontinuity Design: Real Estate Tycoon (40 points)

Its the beginning of 2030 and imagine you have just been promoted to senior executive at a large real estate company (lets call it Sillow). You want to impress your boss and are looking for ways to improve the performance of your realtor agents. You decide that a positive measure would be that any realtor that has a performance rate lower than 80% during the previous year should attend a mandatory retreat to increase sales.

At the end of the year, you ask your analysts to send you the data. This is what you receive:

  • id: An id number for each realtor agent.
  • age: Age of the realtor agent.
  • female: Binary variable indicating if the realtor is female (1) or not (0).
  • performance: The performance of the agent in percentage (ranges from 0 to 100) at the end of 2029.
  • retreat: Binary variable indicating if an agent was assigned or not to the mandatory retreat.
  • sales: An agents final sales for the entire year 2030.
library(tidyverse)
library(rdrobust)
library(rddensity)
library(broom)

sillow <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/website_github/master/exampleSite/content/files/data/sillow3.csv")

1) Determine if process of assigning treatment is rule-based (5 points)

Was assignment to this program based on an arbitrary rule? Is it a good candidate for a regression discontinuity approach? Why or why not?

2) Identify key variables (5 points)

In this example, which variable is your running variable? Which one is your treatment variable? Which one is your outcome of interest?

3) Validity of the RD design (10 points)

We know that our RD is only valid if there is no discontinuity of the potential outcomes at the cutoff, and they are smooth across the threshold.

Use one of the covariates in your dataset and rdplot() and rdrobust() to show support for this last assumption. What should you expect to see if the key assumption holds and why? Interpret your results

4) Estimate a causal effect (15 points)

Estimate a causal effect of this program using a (1) parametric approach (linear regression using the whole sample), and (2) nonparametric approach (using rdrobust).


  1. What is the estimand you are estimating here?
  2. Do your results differ between both models? Why?
  3. Which one do you prefer and why?

Note: For estimating the RD under a parametric approach, remember to create the distance variable we saw in class!

Now your boss says they want to roll out this policy for the whole company, so she needs you to estimate an effect for everyone. She suggests fitting a regression of the outcome on the treatment variable and other covariates. You run the model (because shes your boss). What do you find when you fit this model? Interpret the coefficient for the treatment variable and one covariate (you choose).How would you explain these results to your boss?
